Observations

Age - Loyalty

Observations

Line is near-flat or slightly negative; very low R.

Dense clusters by cohort but no strong linear pattern.

Interpretation

Age alone isnt a good predictor in a straight line.

Suggestions

Dont target on age alone; tailor to cohort instead.

Notes/limits

Possible cohort late-20s/30s peak

Remuneration - Loyalty

Observations

Strong positive relationship; higher pay aligns with more points.

Spread widens at higher remuneration.

Suggestions

Create premium tiers/VIP offers, finance/credit-backed bundles.

Spending score - Loyalty

Observations

Clear upward trend; points increase as spending score rises.

Variance grows at high scores.

Visible clusters around mid-50s and 8090.

Suggestions

Incentivise moves from 4060 to 70+ (tiered perks, bundles, threshold bonuses).

Use spend thresholds in campaigns and retarget mid-spenders.

Monitor diminishing returns & fairness.

Summary

Our linear regressions show spending score is the strongest single predictor of loyalty points, with a clear positive slope and the highest R among the three models. Remuneration (kGBP) is also positively associated with loyalty points, though less strongly than spending score. Age has a weak, near-flat relationship, suggesting it is not a useful standalone predictor of loyalty points. The scatterplots indicate widening spread at higher spending and remuneration (heteroscedasticity), meaning some customers convert additional spend into points more efficiently than others. Residual patterns are broadly centered but not perfectly uniform, so simple linear models capture the main trends but wont explain all variance.

What to explore further: refine the regression by including spending score and remuneration together (multiple linear regression), check coefficient stability, examine residuals (normality and constant variance), and test simple transformations (e.g., log of loyalty points or remuneration) if assumptions look strained.

Suggested actions: prioritize spend-uplift tactics (e.g., clear point thresholds and bundles) and trial value-aligned offers for higher-remuneration customers. Use age mainly for messaging/creative rather than targeting. Continue to document assumptions, note any warnings, and version the cleaned dataset for reuse.

In[33]:
# Create your decision tree regressor. (Baseline, unpruned)
regressor_base = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=RANDOM_STATE)
regressor_base.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Evaluate the model.
def print_metrics(y_tr, y_tr_pred, y_te, y_te_pred, label="Model"):
    mse_tr = mean_squared_error(y_tr, y_tr_pred)
    mse_te = mean_squared_error(y_te, y_te_pred)
    rmse_tr = np.sqrt(mse_tr)
    rmse_te = np.sqrt(mse_te)
    mae_tr  = mean_absolute_error(y_tr, y_tr_pred)
    mae_te  = mean_absolute_error(y_te, y_te_pred)
    r2_tr   = r2_score(y_tr, y_tr_pred)
    r2_te   = r2_score(y_te, y_te_pred)
    print(f"{label}  TRAIN  RMSE: {rmse_tr:.1f} | MAE: {mae_tr:.1f} | R: {r2_tr:.3f}")
    print(f"{label}  TEST   RMSE: {rmse_te:.1f}  | MAE: {mae_te:.1f}  | R: {r2_te:.3f}")

y_pred_train_base = regressor_base.predict(X_train)
y_pred_test_base  = regressor_base.predict(X_test)
print_metrics(y_train, y_pred_train_base, y_test, y_pred_test_base, label="Baseline tree")

Baseline tree  TRAIN  RMSE: 0.0 | MAE: 0.0 | R: 1.000
Baseline tree  TEST   RMSE: 81.3  | MAE: 27.0  | R: 0.996
In[34]:
# Prune the model.
candidates = []
for max_depth in [3, 4, 5, 6]:
    for min_leaf in [1, 5, 10]:
        m = DecisionTreeRegressor(
            random_state=RANDOM_STATE,
            max_depth=max_depth,
            min_samples_leaf=min_leaf
        )
        m.fit(X_train, y_train)
        r2_te = r2_score(y_test, m.predict(X_test))
        candidates.append((max_depth, min_leaf, r2_te, m))

# Pick the best by test R
best_max_depth, best_min_leaf, best_r2_test, best_model = max(candidates, key=lambda t: t[2])
print(f"Best params  max_depth={best_max_depth}, min_samples_leaf={best_min_leaf}, test R={best_r2_test:.3f}")

Best params  max_depth=6, min_samples_leaf=10, test R=0.974
In[35]:
# Fit and plot final model.
regressor_pruned = DecisionTreeRegressor(
    random_state=RANDOM_STATE,
    max_depth=best_max_depth,
    min_samples_leaf=best_min_leaf
)
regressor_pruned.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Evaluate pruned model
y_pred_train_pruned = regressor_pruned.predict(X_train)
y_pred_test_pruned  = regressor_pruned.predict(X_test)
print_metrics(y_train, y_pred_train_pruned, y_test, y_pred_test_pruned, label="Pruned tree")

# Feature importance (which inputs mattered most)
importances = pd.Series(regressor_pruned.feature_importances_, index=feature_cols).sort_values(ascending=False)
print("\nFeature importances:\n", importances)

Insights and observations

Usefulness

The pruned tree generalises well: R(test)=0.974 vs R(train)=0.980. The baseline tree hit R(train)=1.00 (classic overfit) even though test R was very high; pruning trades a little fit for a simpler, more stable model.

Interpretability is high: the model surfaces a small set of clear thresholds that a non-technical audience can act on.

What the tree says (read topdown)

Root split: spending_score 67. This confirms spending_score is the primary driver (feature importance 0.48, very close to remuneration_kgbp 0.51; age 0.01 and is negligible).

Low spend ( 15.5): very low loyalty; even higher remuneration rarely compensates - low ROI segment.

Mid spend (15.567): loyalty improves as remuneration crosses 33.6k and 68.9k kGBP; adding spend above 55 helps.

High spend (> 67): remuneration thresholds at 43.9k, 74.2k, 80.8k, 88.6k separate high - very high loyalty bands; a minor spending nudge around 71.5 further boosts value.

How to use this for the business

Tiered offers by spending:

15.5: light, low-cost nurture only.

15.567: threshold bonuses (e.g., extra points at 55 and 67) to push into the high tier.

67: protect value with VIP perks; add a micro-nudge around 71.5.

Remuneration bands: add premium/VIP benefits above 74k and 88.6k; below 44k, use value bundles rather than premium credit perks.

Age: do not target on age; use only for messaging tone/channels.

Caveats: validate thresholds with A/B tests, monitor fairness, and re-check stability with K-fold CV.

Summary

Our decision tree gives a clear, easy way to explain loyalty points. After trimming the tree to keep it simple, it still explains most of the differences we see in the data and behaves reliably on new customers. The first and most important split is spending score. Customers with a spending score above roughly sixty-seven tend to earn many more loyalty points. Income also matters a lot. Higher income usually means more points, and several income cut-offs separate good customers from great ones. Age barely moves the needle here, so its better for message tone and channel choice, not for targeting.

What to do with this: For low spenders (around fifteen or below), keep costs low and use light-touch nurture. For mid spenders (roughly fifteen to sixty-seven), push them over key thresholds with bonus points, bundles, and clear spend more, earn more offers. For high spenders, protect and grow value with VIP benefits and premium offers. For higher-income customers, offer premium tiers and early access; for lower-income customers, focus on value packs rather than credit or luxury perks.

These rules are simple to explain to the business and can be A/B tested quickly.

## 3. Elbow and silhouette methods 
# Standardise features for k-means.
scaler = StandardScaler()
X = df3[['remuneration_kgbp','spending_score']].values
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Determine the number of clusters: Elbow method.
ks = list(range(2, 11))
inertias = []
for k in ks:
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=RANDOM_STATE, n_init=10)
    km.fit(X_scaled)
    inertias.append(km.inertia_)

plt.plot(ks, inertias, marker='o')
plt.xticks(ks)
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Inertia (within-cluster SSE)')
plt.title('Elbow Method')
plt.show()

# Determine the number of clusters: Silhouette method.
sil_scores = []
for k in ks:
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=RANDOM_STATE, n_init=10)
    labels = km.fit_predict(X_scaled)
    sil = silhouette_score(X_scaled, labels)
    sil_scores.append(sil)

plt.plot(ks, sil_scores, marker='o')
plt.xticks(ks)
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette score (higher is better)')
plt.title('Silhouette Method')
plt.show()

print(pd.DataFrame({'k': ks, 'silhouette': sil_scores, 'inertia': inertias}))

## 4. Evaluate k-means model at different values of *k* 
def plot_kmeans(k):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=RANDOM_STATE, n_init=10)
    labels = km.fit_predict(X_scaled)
    centers_scaled = km.cluster_centers_
    centers = scaler.inverse_transform(centers_scaled)

    # Attach labels for inspection
    out = df3.copy()
    out[f'cluster_k{k}'] = labels
    print(f"\nCluster sizes for k={k}:")
    print(out[f'cluster_k{k}'].value_counts().sort_index())

    # Plot
    palette = sns.color_palette(n_colors=k)
    sns.scatterplot(
        x=out['remuneration_kgbp'], y=out['spending_score'],
        hue=out[f'cluster_k{k}'], palette=palette, s=40, alpha=0.8, legend='full'
    )
    plt.scatter(centers[:,0], centers[:,1], marker='X', s=200, edgecolor='black')
    plt.title(f'k-means clustering (k={k})')
    plt.legend(title='Cluster')
    plt.show()

for k in [5]:
    plot_kmeans(k)

Insights and observations

Overview

Using k-means on remuneration_kgbp and spending_score, k = 5 (silhouette 0.585) produced five clear, business-meaningful segments.

a) Groups identified (plain-English descriptions)

C0 High income, High spend (centroid 73k, 82): Premium customers with consistently high engagement.

C1 Low income, Low spend ( 20k, 20): Low capacity and low activity; low immediate ROI.

C2 High income, Low spend ( 74.6k, 17.5): Affluent but under-engaged; large headroom.

C3 Low income, High spend ( 20.4k, 79.4): Deal-driven enthusiasts; value-sensitive, very active.

C4 Mid income, Mid spend (Core) ( 44.4k, 49.5): Broad middle with clear uplift potential.

b) Relative sizes of the groups

C4 Core: 774 (38.7%) - largest lever

C0 HighHigh: 356 (17.8%)

C2 HighLow: 330 (16.5%)

C1 LowLow: 271 (13.6%)

C3 LowHigh: 269 (13.4%)

c) Specific actions / target priorities

C4 Core (midmid): Run tiered spend-threshold bonuses (e.g., 55 to 67), seasonal bundles, and cross-sells to lift into C0.

C0 HighHigh (vip): Protect & expand with VIP perks, early access, higher point multipliers on premium categories, concierge-style service.

C2 HighLow (affluent under-engaged): Activation campaigns (welcome/first-purchase boosters), personalised recommendations, premium category trials.

C3 LowHigh (enthusiasts): Maintain high perceived value via non-cash perks, limited-time boosts; set margin guards and avoid credit-heavy offers.

C1 LowLow (nurture): Low-cost nurture: value packs, app/email prompts, basic earn rates; cap rewards to keep CAC and reward cost low.

Notes: Use age only for messaging tone/channels, not targeting. Track lift in spending_score and loyalty_points by cluster to validate ROI.

Summary

We grouped customers into five clear segments based on income and spending. Think of it as finding look-alike crowds so we can talk to each one the right way.

Core (about 4 in 10 customers): mid income, mid spend. This is our biggest lever. Give simple spend a bit more, earn a lot more offers and bundles to move them up.

VIPs (about 2 in 10): high income, high spend. Keep them loyal with early access, premium perks and occasional high-value bonuses.

Affluent but under-active (about 1 in 10): high income, low spend. Wake them up with welcome/first-purchase boosts and recommendations for premium categories.

Value enthusiasts (about 1 in 10): low income, high spend. They respond to strong value. Use time-limited boosters and non-cash perks, but watch margin.

Low activity (about 1 in 10): low income, low spend. Keep costs lowsimple nurture, value packs, app/email reminders.

What to do next: tag these segments in the CRM, run small A/B tests per group (e.g., threshold bonuses for Core, VIP perks for VIPs), and track two numbers for each segmentspending score and loyalty pointsto confirm whats working and where to push harder.

Insights

Findings from word clouds (after cleaning and removing stopwords)

Reviews are full of product/use words: game, play, fun, tiles, cards, time, book, set, piece. This suggests people talk about how they use the products and what they liked in play.

Summaries lean heavily on rating phrases: five, stars, great, fun, love, good, four, expansion, kids, cute. Summaries are short and often just say five stars, which explains why they look more positive than reviews.

So what? In listings and ads, lead with fun / great / easy to play language and show star ratings clearly. For families, highlight kids / family / expansion angles.

Frequency distribution (most common words)

Reviews: game, great, fun, play, like, love, cards, tiles, time, good, would, book.

Summaries: stars, five, game, great, fun, love, good, four, expansion, kids, cute. This split (usage terms in reviews vs. rating terms in summaries) supports using feature/benefit copy in long descriptions and ratings/badges in short spaces (thumbnails, cards).

Sentiment (polarity) what tone do customers use?

Reviews (n1,961): mean +0.21, median +0.18, 25% +0.04, 75% +0.35; range 1.0 to +1.0.

Summaries (n1,961): mean +0.22, median +0.10, 25% 0.00, 75% +0.48; range 1.0 to +1.0.

Histograms show many neutral-to-positive comments and a long positive tail; a smaller set is clearly negative.

So what? Overall tone is favourable. Reviews (longer text) carry balanced opinions; summaries (short text) skew more positive (many five stars).

Subjectivity (how opinionated vs. factual)

Reviews cluster around 0.40.7 moderately subjective (opinions + some facts).

Summaries show many near 0 (just five stars) plus a spread up to 1.0.

So what? Pull phrases from reviews for authentic quotes, and use star counts from summaries for quick-impact visuals.

Actionable recommendations

Merch & copy: Feature fun, easy to play, great, and family/kids benefits high up.

Badging: Put Five-star signals on product tiles and ads.

Upsell: Promote expansions to happy buyers; they appear often in summaries.

Support watchlist: A small negative segment exists; periodically sample those comments to catch themes (e.g., missing pieces, quality). Turn frequent issues into FAQs or fixes.

Notes & limits (for your report)

TextBlob gives a quick sentiment score but can miss sarcasm and domain slang.

Cleaning kept English words and removed punctuation; that can drop some emojis and brand terms.

Results describe this dataset (Turtle Games reviews); repeat monthly to spot shifts.

Summary

Most customer comments are neutral to positive, with a strong tilt toward positive. Short summary lines often read like quick ratings (five stars, great, fun), while longer reviews talk about real use: game/play, tiles/cards, time with family/kids, and expansions. This tells us shoppers care about how easy and fun the product is to use, and they notice quality time and add-ons.

What to explore further: pull out a few common themes (e.g., easy to learn, great for kids,) to see which phrases drive better sales or fewer returns. Recheck the pattern each month to catch shifts (seasonality, new releases). Skim the small set of negative comments to spot fixable issues.

What to do now:

Lead product copy with fun, easy to play, and family/kids benefits.

Surface star ratings prominently on product tiles, ads, and search results.

Suggest expansions to happy buyers as a natural next step.

Create short replies for common concerns (e.g., missing pieces, quality), and turn repeated issues into quick FAQs.

Keep a light human review on headlines and sensitive claims.

Overall, the tone supports marketing that is simple, upbeat, family-friendly, and clear about value.
